The aforementioned Paillier homomorphic cryptosystem is proved to be indistinguishability against Chosen Plaintext Attack (CPA) [16] based on decisional composite residuosity problem, which means the ciphertexts will leakage no bit of information about the plaintexts.

III. SECURITY REQUIREMENTS AND SYSTEM OVERVIEW
A. Security Requirements
Different from Hitaj et al. [17] where the learning participants are considered as the active attackers to infer other users‚Äô private training data, our security model assumes that the central server is the untrusted (honest-but-curious) adversary while all the participants are seen as trusted entities. Honest-but-curious server means that it will faithfully follow the designed federated learning protocol but attempt to infer private information from each user‚Äôs local update. In this situation, to prevent the indirect privacy leakage of users‚Äô updated gradients, the following security requirements must be guaranteed.
‚Ä¢ ConÔ¨Ådentiality: Protecting the users‚Äô uploaded gradient vectors from the untrusted server, even if there exists an external attacker who can eavesdrop the communication channels or collude with the server, although the latter is not the mainly concerned in our work.
‚Ä¢ Authentication: Ensures that all the local updates are really from the authorized participants and the received updates cannot be denied by participants.
‚Ä¢ Privacy-preserving: As long as the conÔ¨Ådentiality of gradients and the authentication of participants can be guaranteed, the privacy of sensitive information embedded in the gradient vectors can also be protected.
Since an untrusted and knowledgeable server can infer sensitive information embedded in each participant‚Äôs local gradients (e.g., gradient inference attack [9]), it is necessary to provide a strong privacy guarantee against the untrusted server. Thus, the following objectives should be achieved. 1) Security and privacy: the above-stated security requirements should be satisÔ¨Åed; 2) Accuracy: PEFL should perform high model accuracy; 3) EfÔ¨Åciency: the computational overheads of cryptosystem is required to be low.

