V. SECURITY ANALYSIS

In this section, we present the security analysis of our PEFL scheme. In particular, according to the security requirements and design goals described in section III, our security analysis will focus on the participant authentication, conÔ¨Ådentiality, and privacy-preserving. A. Participant Authentication

The registration and authentication phase in our designed PEFL scheme basically relies on the extended Schnorr‚Äôs signature and veriÔ¨Åcation mechanism [19], which is proved to be secure based on the discrete logarithm assumption. The correctness of participants authentication can be represented as follow.

gŒ≤i yiH2(Œ±i) = g g ei‚àíxiH2(Œ±i) xiH2(Œ±i) = gei = Œ±i. (9)

Here, we demonstrate that the participant i‚Äôs identity can be efÔ¨Åciently authenticated as long as the discrete logarithm assumption holds.
Practically, it is impossible that an attacker can Ô¨Ånd a collision e‚Ä≤i to fabricate the registration knowledge {yi, Œ±i, Œ≤i} because the value of xi was selected privately and kept at the participant side. Besides, even if an untrusted server can obtain i‚Äôs real identiÔ¨Åer IDi and current time stamp T St, it still cannot get the real value of ei. That is mainly because ei was further hidden by using a secure one-way hash function H1 and a secretly blind factor ki. Therefore, without the value of ei, the possibility of an untrusted server obtaining the authentication private key xi is negligible.
B. ConÔ¨Ådentiality and Privacy-Preserving

To prevent the disclosure of the participants‚Äô training data

privacy, we utilize the Paillier cryptosystem to encrypt the up-

loaded gradient vectors and aggregate the ciphertext based on

the additively homomorphic property. In this way, the update

